Microservices
Small, independent, and loosely coupled (small development team)
• Each service is a separate codebase
●
• Services can be deployed independently (no application rebuilt)
●
• Services are responsible for persisting their own data or external state
(no data persistence layer)
• Services communicate with each other by using well-defined APIs
Internal implementation details of each service are hidden from other services
Services don't need to share the same technology stack, libraries, or frameworks
●
●
Reference: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/architecture/

Microservices: Best Practices
Model services around the business domain
• Decentralize everything
• Individual teams responsible for designing and building services. Avoid sharing code or data schemas
Data storage to be private to service that owns the data. Use the best storage for each service and data type
• Services communicate through well-designed APIs. Avoid leaking implementation details
• Avoid coupling between services (no shared database schemas and rigid communication protocols)
●
Offload cross-cutting concerns, such as authentication and SSL termination, to the gateway
Keep domain knowledge out of the gateway
• Services should have loose coupling and high functional cohesion
• Isolate failures: Use resiliency strategies to prevent failures within a service from cascading.
●
●

Best Practices

Think adaptive and elastic
Design APIs for platform independent and evolution of applications

• Service Evolution: Evolve while keep support of existing applications
Design loosely coupled components
Design applications to be self healing when failures happen
Build redundancy into application to avoid single points of failure
Minimize coordination between application services to achieve scalability

Coupling
• Domain Coupling
●
●
●
●
Pass through Coupling
One microservice passes data to another microservice because it is needed by some other further downstream microservice
• Common Coupling
One Microservice the user of the functionality of the other Microservice
• Content Coupling
An upstream service reaches into the internals of a downstream service and changes its internal state
●
Two or more microservices make use of a common set of data
●
Temporal Coupling
One microservice needs to call another microservice in a synchronous way
